posts.name: Molly McCormick
posts.cooked:
Question â€“ how do NEO motors compare to 775Pros? My team has used them in the past, but hasnâ€™t in a couple of years, so Iâ€™ve never had any experience with them. This year my team used basically all NEOs for anything that needed more than a NEO 550 could do, but Iâ€™m going through old lessons and reading that 775Pros are good for whenever you need more than a 550. For teams that have used both 775Pros and NEOs, what are your thoughts? And when do you choose one over the other?

Also, we also switched to using MaxPlanetary gearboxes instead of VersaPlanetary because of their compatibility with NEOs. If we do start using 775Pros again, is it better to use them with VersaPlanetary, since theyâ€™re from Vex, or are MaxPlanetaries still better?
You can look up some of the differences yourself, but it really comes down to brushed (775Pro) vs brushless (NEO).

Hereâ€™s a really good starting point for info about FRC-legal motors: https://motors.vex.com/

775Pros are Brushed motors, just like CIMs, MiniCIMs, Bag motors, RS-550â€™s, etc. This means they have metal brushes that contact the rotor of the motor. Theyâ€™re super simple mechanically,  generally cheaper to produce, and can function without any kind of motor control (apply power to the leads, and it runs!) image 778Ã—560 33.7 KB

image 778Ã—560 33.7 KB

image 778Ã—560 33.7 KB

Neos, Neo 550â€™s, Falcons are all Brushless , which have a number of advantages over brushed motors, including them being lighter, they produce less heat, and have less electrical noise. However, they require motor controllers. This isnâ€™t a major downside in FRC, because we tend to use motor controllers anyway. image 606Ã—636 38.9 KB

image 606Ã—636 38.9 KB

image 606Ã—636 38.9 KB

Given a low torque application, I would personally use Neo 550â€™s over 775pros. Given a higher torque application I would generally use NEOs, Falcons, or CIM/MiniCIMs.

This does, however, depend on what resources you have on hand, how much space you have for the motor in your mechanism, etc.

Pictures taken from: https://motors.vex.com/brushed-brushless (theyâ€™re GIFs when viewed on Vexâ€™s page!)

posts.name: Billfred Leverette (he/him/not Bill)
posts.cooked:
@Kevin_Leonard â€™s excellent post is incorporated by reference.

At this point, we are pretty much all NEO and NEO 550.  We have some RedLine stuff kicking around (and used one in our 2021 rebuild out of cheapskatery), but itâ€™s really tough to beat the power, built-in current limiting, and ease of integrating encoders.

Weâ€™ve also used full-size NEOs in places where we mightâ€™ve normally only needed a NEO 550 (or before that, the 775Pro or RedLine) just because it packaged better.  For example, take our 2020 yeet drums to kick out game pieces into the lower port. Two NEOs on that is hilariously overpowered, but it wouldâ€™ve required significantly more manufacturing (and probably a chain or belt run) to package in a planetary gearbox like we did on the conveyor belts where we had the space (note the two blue Sport gearboxes on the diagonal member).

posts.name: Tom Line
posts.cooked:
To add to all the other information,

775s are a small, very high power brushed motor.  They have a much higher RPM than a NEO or falcon, with around 15% less power.  As a result, for pretty much any application you are going to need to use a gearbox or other significant reduction and itâ€™s going to have to be more than you would need for a Neo or Falcon to achieve the same speed.  In most situations the 775 is going to end up being very comparable to the neo or falcon in weight when you take the gearing into account.

The 775 is physically smaller than a Neo or Falcon and that works to its benefit, however the smaller size also comes with reduced thermal capacity.  A 775 will fail much faster than a Neo or Falcon.  In addition, the way most teams gear down the motors (planetaries) will result in the overall length of the 775, Neo, and Falcon being very compariable.

In short.

775:

Slightly smaller

Slightly lighter

Slightly less power

Requires more reduction

Burns out very easily in comparison

Requires external encoder for closed loop control

Neo/Falcon

Slightly larger

Slightly heavier

Slightly more powerful

Requires less reduction

Increased weight means additional thermal mass and durability

Integral encoder

There are vanishingly few situations where a 775 has a compelling use case.  There might be a few, but I canâ€™t think of any where I would legitimately use one.

That said, weâ€™ve found neo550â€™s to be acceptable, but their reduced thermal mass also means one mistake ends in a toasted motor.  So in that vein, there are fewer and fewer situations where I will willing spec a neo550 unless Iâ€™m forced into it because of space considerations.

This year we used 550s on our swerve steering, turret, and hood.  But only because we didnâ€™t have the money to spring for Falcons, and Falcons were rarely available.

We actually gifted all of our brushless motors (around 40 775s and a comparable number of cims and motor controllers) to a low budget team earlier this year because we doubted weâ€™d use them and they needed them far more than we did.

550s work just fine with versas.  Thatâ€™s what we used this year.
Arenâ€™t 775s around 4x less powerful than NEOs/Falcons? IIRC the 775 has a stall torque of less than 1 N-m, whereas the NEO and Falcon have around 4.

posts.name: Tom Line
posts.cooked:
That is a typical misconception when folks are learning about motors.

Torque is a measure of force.  It is not a measure of power.  Force can be changed by changing your lever arm (gear reduction).  So once you slow down the 775 through a gear reduction, the torque will be a lot more compariable.

Total power is measured in watts.  340 something for a 775, and 400 ish for a neo/falcon.  So roughly 18% different.

posts.name: Billfred Leverette (he/him/not Bill)
posts.cooked:
Tom_Line:

Total power is measured in watts. 340 something for a 775, and 400 ish for a neo/falcon.

Iâ€™d put it 450-500 for the NEO and Falcon 500.  Both are rated for more (VEX tests them at 516 for NEO, 783 for Falcon 500), but consider that past about 500 watts youâ€™re placing a bet on your 40A breakerâ€™s trip times (in that 12.5 volts * 40 amps = 500 watts).  That can be made a safer bet by designing around the breakerâ€™s rated trip times, using the better-rated REV breakers, only using new ones that havenâ€™t been tripped, and by ensuring your electronics donâ€™t start a match hotâ€“but because we live in a world where Goofy Things Happen, thereâ€™s always some small amount of gamble to it.

posts.name: Chris Bale
posts.cooked:
775s are great power for the size (we even used them in our drive systems back in the day), but all the advantages FRC brushless motors have (performance, integrated sensors, low speed torque, etc.) make them hard to justify anymore (assuming cost is no issue for you) in my opinion.

That said though, when you consider the difficulty (extra steps, weight, size, etc.) of integrating a NEO/Falcon into a planetary gearbox or other lighter-duty mechanisms, and the huge performance gap between those motors and the NEO550, it does make me wish someone would develop a 775-scale brushless motor for similar types of applications where you might want to use a NEO550 but need more power (but not enough to justify the size/weight or a CIM-class motor like a NEO/Falcon).

posts.name: Clayton Yocom
posts.cooked:
Billfred:

but consider that past about 500 watts youâ€™re placing a bet on your 40A breakerâ€™s trip times (in that 12.5 volts * 40 amps = 500 watts).

Just to clarify this, the quoted specs are 450-500 watts of output power, to create that peak power requires a lot more than 450-500 watts of input power.

For referenceâ€™s sake 500 watts of input power creates the following amount of output power: NEO: vex quotes 343 watts, revâ€™s datasheet says 380 watts Falcon: 420 watts 775 Pro: 297 watts

Peak power is (generally) at a relatively low point on the efficiency curve. NEO: 500 out @ 1095 in Falcon: 783 out @ 1552 in 775 Pro: 347 out @ 806 in

posts.name: FrankJ
posts.cooked:
A couple of advantages of the 775s: Motor/controller combo slightly to lots less expensive. No risk of encoder cable being snagged. This is important if your motor is in a exposed position like on a intake. Also if the motor needs to mounted a distance away from the motor controller there is no encoder cable to worry about.

A big disadvantage of a 775s is they depend on high RPM for cooling. They do not do well highly loaded or at stalled conditions.

In most other cases the brush-less motors are better.

posts.name: Allen Nuttle
posts.cooked: Current limiting is your friend.  We always apply this, especially with NEO550s, and have it set so a stalled motor has a lot more time before it cooks.  When 100% of the input power is being turned to heat, a fan can also buy you some time, but probably not indefinite time.

posts.name: Allen Nuttle
posts.cooked:
Here â€™s something worth considering:

20A Limit - Motor survived full 220s test.

40A Limit - Motor failure at approximately 27s.

60A Limit - Motor failure at approximately 5.5s

80A Limit* - Motor failure at approximately 2.0s

*This is the default Smart Current Limit in the SPARK MAX. It is highly recommended to adjust the Smart Current Limit when driving the NEO 550.

Do you really want all the current when it will smoke the motor in 2 seconds?  You should never stall a NEO550 (all motors hate being stalled), but if you are going to run it slow/stalled, current limits are really essential.

The motor windings can only dissipate so much heat to the air, and will not all be kept at the same temperature by even a whole lot of airflow.  It would be interesting to see how long a NEO550, with independent forced-air cooling, could survive 80A.  My guess is it would still be under a minuteâ€¦
